    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_15692941" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/15692941" />
    <a title="Keith" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/810875-keith"><img alt="Keith" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/m_50x66-82093808bca726cb3249a493fbd3bd0f.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/15692941?book_show_action=true">Feb 18, 2008</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Keith" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Keith" href="/user/show/810875-keith">Keith</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>


          <div><span class="uitext greyText">Recommends it for: </span>
           <span class="uitext reviewText">serious readers</span></div>

        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer15692941" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2778291166137260663">I had never read Oe, although I was aware that he had won the Nobel Prize. The blurbs on the cover report that this is his most popular book, published around the time I graduated from college in the late sixties. I didn&apos;t know what to expect, but was surprised to discover a Japanese existentialist, a student of twentieth century French extentialist literature. His writing style reflects the influence of Sartre, Camus, and Beckett. I had read considerable French existentialism during my college </span>
  <span id="freeText2778291166137260663" style="display:none">I had never read Oe, although I was aware that he had won the Nobel Prize. The blurbs on the cover report that this is his most popular book, published around the time I graduated from college in the late sixties. I didn't know what to expect, but was surprised to discover a Japanese existentialist, a student of twentieth century French extentialist literature. His writing style reflects the influence of Sartre, Camus, and Beckett. I had read considerable French existentialism during my college years, and had even tried (unsuccessfully) to read what was considered to the the best philosophical framework of the movement, Martin Heidegger's BEING AND TIME. When I entered seminary to begin studying for ministry I announed that I was an existentialist, although there was really no clear definition of what existentialism was. Time covered those early impulses over. Oe uncovered them. This is an astonishingly moral work, although the foundation of Oe's morality is not framed in the more familiar Judeo-Christian orientation of the west. In the novel Bird, a young Japanese man living in Tokyo, descends into a life and death moral turmoil over the birth of his first son who is born with a curiously damaged head. As Bird struggles to embrace this "monster" as his son, he leaves his wife behind in the hospital and enters (in more ways than one) into the life of a college classmate who is grieving her young husband's suicide. It is a young man's moral struggle to rise above his dreams for himself and his raging passions.<br />The blurb on the cover announces that it is close to "a perfect contemporary novel." After reading it for the first time years after its appearance I think that I could have written that blurb. This is serious literature. </span>
  <a data-text-id="2778291166137260663" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

