<div id="review_618430597" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/618430597" />
    <a title="Smiley " class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2580971-smiley"><img alt="Smiley " src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1525349534p2/2580971.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/618430597?book_show_action=true">May 18, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Smiley " class="user" itemprop="url" name="Smiley " href="/user/show/2580971-smiley">Smiley </a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9784805306413" href="/book/show/17375975-a-personal-matter">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2580971-smiley?shelf=fiction">fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2580971-smiley?shelf=japan">japan</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer618430597" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1060278566489991278">3.75 stars<br/><br/>Reading this novel by Kenzaburo Oe was nearly a mission impossible to me. On August 11 last year (2012), I started reading it, reached Chapter 4 and quit there. I didn&apos;t find it readable enough to find any motive to read any further, it was seemingly hopeless to read more till I could make it with his 13-chapter &quot;The Silent Cry&quot;. I think Oe has tried to convey his message or voice by means of his novels written out of his bitter, tormented and enigmatic mind. Surprisingly this novel al</span>
  <span id="freeText1060278566489991278" style="display:none">3.75 stars<br /><br />Reading this novel by Kenzaburo Oe was nearly a mission impossible to me. On August 11 last year (2012), I started reading it, reached Chapter 4 and quit there. I didn't find it readable enough to find any motive to read any further, it was seemingly hopeless to read more till I could make it with his 13-chapter "The Silent Cry". I think Oe has tried to convey his message or voice by means of his novels written out of his bitter, tormented and enigmatic mind. Surprisingly this novel also has 13 chapters and I don't know why, I think this remark might be clarified by the author himself somewhere.<br /><br />Why has his mind been in trouble? We can find this from various sources, please let me quote one from Wikipedia, "the writer describes the pain involved in accepting his brain-damaged son into his life." (<a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kenzaburo_Oe">http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kenzabur...</a>) In this globalized world nowadays, we have read or heard a lot about 'crisis' vs. 'opportunity' and we can see how Oe has revealed his expertise by writing his novels subtly depicting his crises in his characters as well as how over time the text and the writing process can gradually transform one of his weaknesses into one of his strengths, that is, his opportunity. This is amazing since few authors worldwide can keep doing like him till he was awarded one of the most prestigious literary prizes in the world and his admirers, I think, have long since been delighted because he rightly deserves the Nobel Prize in 1994 due to his literary dedication and unique works.</span>
  <a data-text-id="1060278566489991278" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


