<div id="review_3983129217" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3983129217" />
    <a title="Elena Sala" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/58119141-elena-sala"><img alt="Elena Sala" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1469638554p2/58119141.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3983129217?book_show_action=true">May 30, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Elena Sala" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Elena Sala" href="/user/show/58119141-elena-sala">Elena Sala</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9788433966193" href="/book/show/70860.Una_cuesti_n_personal">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/58119141-elena-sala?shelf=asia">asia</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/58119141-elena-sala?shelf=japan">japan</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3983129217" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3787314510487082932">A PERSONAL MATTER (1964) is a semi-autobiographical novel written by Kenzaburo Oe after the birth of his autistic son. Since then, apparently, the theme of disability is present frequently in his work .<br/><br/>Bird, the protagonist, is a young married man and an irresponsible dreamer, dissatisfied with his mediocre job and troubled by the responsibility of supporting a family. While his wife is in hospital giving birth he headed to a shop to buy some maps of Africa as his latest escapist fantasy is abou</span>
  <span id="freeText3787314510487082932" style="display:none">A PERSONAL MATTER (1964) is a semi-autobiographical novel written by Kenzaburo Oe after the birth of his autistic son. Since then, apparently, the theme of disability is present frequently in his work .<br /><br />Bird, the protagonist, is a young married man and an irresponsible dreamer, dissatisfied with his mediocre job and troubled by the responsibility of supporting a family. While his wife is in hospital giving birth he headed to a shop to buy some maps of Africa as his latest escapist fantasy is about traveling to Africa. Unfortunately, his child was born with a brain hernia (he describes him as a "two headed-monster") and the doctors can offer only the most sombre prognosis . Overwhelmed by this news, he arrives to the conclusion that his future will be ruined by his disabled son so he tries to persuade the doctors to let the baby die. For Bird, the baby is a horrible vegetable, a monstrous creature, and it made no sense to him to attempt a surgery to save his life, or to fight for his future. And off he goes, to a binge of alcohol and sex, shame and humiliation, and to await the call that would confirm his baby had expired.<br /><br />This novel is cruel, intense and brutal in its honesty. It reminded me of Malcolm Lowry's Under the Volcano, and its description of a descent into hell. So, reader, be warned, because the subject matter is really ugly.</span>
  <a data-text-id="3787314510487082932" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


