    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2961342076" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2961342076" />
    <a title="Bhzd Sdgh" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/59633725-bhzd-sdgh"><img alt="Bhzd Sdgh" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/m_50x66-82093808bca726cb3249a493fbd3bd0f.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2961342076?book_show_action=true">Sep 02, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Bhzd Sdgh" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Bhzd Sdgh" href="/user/show/59633725-bhzd-sdgh">Bhzd Sdgh</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/59633725-bhzd-sdgh?shelf=novel">novel</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/59633725-bhzd-sdgh?shelf=japanese-novels">japanese-novels</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2961342076" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5608692636579470800">I think the real horror of the situation the protagonist of <i>A Personal Matter</i> finds himself in can only be comprehended by those who have (physically or mentally) abnormal children. The simple fact that you know you have the rest of your life cut out for you by an infant who may never be able to take care of itself in any way is tragic and horrific enough. Therefore, you only need a short-lived background in self-indulgence and masochism in order to plunge yourself into the darkest depths of hel</span>
  <span id="freeText5608692636579470800" style="display:none">I think the real horror of the situation the protagonist of <i>A Personal Matter</i> finds himself in can only be comprehended by those who have (physically or mentally) abnormal children. The simple fact that you know you have the rest of your life cut out for you by an infant who may never be able to take care of itself in any way is tragic and horrific enough. Therefore, you only need a short-lived background in self-indulgence and masochism in order to plunge yourself into the darkest depths of hell.<br />And this is precisely what happens to Bird in <i>A Personal Matter</i>. The novel starts with Bird leafing through different books and maps about Africa, the land he has been dreaming about traveling to all his life. Then there is this fight with a bunch of teenagers or whatever which paints a quite unfeeling and unpromising picture for what is about to come. And then there is the baby.<br />It is just an infant, for sure. Incapable of doing the simplest routine tasks (as is the case with all human infants) it will die if it is left to its own resources. Yet, its tenacity to grab on to life despite all the unfavorable conditions turns it into a monster for the protagonist of the novel. <br />The trajectory Bird moves through is quite dramatic and unconventional: Bird gives up on all his responsibilities and dives headlong into an ocean of alcohol, sex and remembering the past; he drifts off from his wife; he is fired; he is a total mess. Yet, at the very end of the novel, through what might be called some sort of revelation or something, he rushes back to the infant, rescues it, and takes on the responsibility of becoming the father to a child who might turn out to be a total invalid. Yes, the ending sounded a bit forced and unnatural to me as well. But then, I thought to myself: what would a normal guy do in such a circumstance? I mean, how often do we take our abnormal infants to quacks so as to kill them and rid ourselves of the responsibility? To my experience, rarely. Most of the time, we just go through with whatever life puts before us. And we end up with vegetable children who are incapable of living a normal life.<br /><b>However, there was this question that kept popping up in my mind while reading this novel: what is a completely moral act? Is it moral to keep an abnormal infant alive, an infant who may have to live a life of torture, isolation and limitation? Is it moral to give privilege to life no matter what? What would I have asked for, if I had the chance to choose between death on the one hand, and a miserable vegetable life on the other?</b><br />Similar to other works of Japanese literature, this novel raises similar important and basic questions about life, morality and death; which is what makes it a brilliant novel. And, it is preoccupied with sex and stuff, again similar to almost every Japanese novel I've read so far.<br />Other than that, it does not contain what I usually look for in Japanese novels: literary prose describing strange, and beautiful landscapes of Japan.</span>
  <a data-text-id="5608692636579470800" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


