<div id="review_1580470733" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1580470733" />
    <a title="Asher Deep" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/41143456-asher-deep"><img alt="Asher Deep" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1600494669p2/41143456.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1580470733?book_show_action=true">Mar 15, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Asher Deep" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Asher Deep" href="/user/show/41143456-asher-deep">Asher Deep</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/41143456-asher-deep?shelf=favorites">favorites</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1580470733" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15961023970191655941">I&apos;ve seen quite a few people display their disgust at the book and its main character; also seen quite a few people complain that there&apos;s no humor in this book; I personally couldn&apos;t understand both those complaints.<br/><br/>First, humor, albeit dark, is present throughout the book; whether it&apos;s the scene with the doctors or whether it&apos;s most of the scenes with our main character, Bird. The way the humor balances the dark subject matter of the book. I&apos;m in awe at how Oe managed to blend the lightness and</span>
  <span id="freeText15961023970191655941" style="display:none">I've seen quite a few people display their disgust at the book and its main character; also seen quite a few people complain that there's no humor in this book; I personally couldn't understand both those complaints.<br /><br />First, humor, albeit dark, is present throughout the book; whether it's the scene with the doctors or whether it's most of the scenes with our main character, Bird. The way the humor balances the dark subject matter of the book. I'm in awe at how Oe managed to blend the lightness and the harrowing parts of the book; Oe pulls this off marvelously.<br /><br />Second, as for Bird: he does in the beginning look like a horrible person so much so that the reader might feel he/she's above Bird, but as you go deeper in the book and past the surface-level critique, Bird seems as despicable as we might be on our worst days. Oe makes us countenance the despicable parts of ourselves that might be latent due to our suppressing it; our first thoughts aren't usually all that civilized and moral, and the reality Oe throws Bird in--you realize finally--doesn't seem to be one that would yield the most rational of one's actions.<br /><br />This is a great, funny book with a concise and lucid prose style. This was my first Japanese novel: I look forward to exploring Japanese literature more now and to reading other works of Mr. Oe. </span>
  <a data-text-id="15961023970191655941" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


